      <div class="prose reveal">
        <p>I lead with discipline and urgency. The work I'm proudest of has nearly always looked the same from the outside — quiet, on schedule, unremarkable in the moment — and only later revealed itself as a structural shift.</p>
        <p>That's the bias of my practice. I don't optimize for the announcement. I optimize for what's still standing eighteen months after the press release stops circulating, when the team that inherits the work has to operate the thing for real.</p>
        <h2>How I think about the work</h2>
        <p><strong>Trust is a system property.</strong> The most expensive failures I've watched up close were never failures of intelligence or even effort — they were failures of interface between teams who had each done their part correctly.</p>
        <p><strong>Pace is a posture.</strong> I move with deliberate urgency. The cost of being late is almost always larger than the cost of deciding.</p>
        <p><strong>Write it down.</strong> If a decision isn't recorded, it didn't happen.</p>
      </div>
